{
  "doc_id": "11821",
  "text": "LV vectors have been used successfully in clinical trials, in a first instance for the treatment of rare diseases, in particular, of primary immunodeficiencies [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] and in neurodegenerative storage diseases. [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] However, their application for the treatment of more frequent genetic and acquired diseases, including treatment of β-thalassemia, [CITATION_5] Parkinson's disease, [CITATION_6] and chimeric antigen receptor-based immunotherapy of cancer, [CITATION_7] has been assessed in clinics with exciting outcomes. This means that manufacturing technology becomes a critical issue in view of the implementation of these novel therapies for routine use.",
